{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"call_852683de17b343c6ac7a68","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":22,"case_id":"arb-ex06-20260630013224","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\n\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\n\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\n\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\n\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\n\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\n\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\n\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\n\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\n\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\n\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\n\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\n\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\n\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\n\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\n\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\n\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\n\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\n\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\n\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\n\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\n\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\n\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\n\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\n\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\n\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\n\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\n\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\n\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\n\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\n\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\n\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\n\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\n\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\n\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\n\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\n\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\n\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\n\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\n\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\n\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\n\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\n\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\n\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\n\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\n\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-S1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\nBytes: 3899\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\nBytes: 2786\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\n\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887695,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":22}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_852683de17b343c6ac7a68","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":22,"case_id":"arb-ex06-20260630013224","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\n\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\n\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\n\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\n\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\n\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\n\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\n\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\n\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\n\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\n\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\n\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\n\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\n\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\n\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\n\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\n\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\n\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\n\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\n\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\n\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\n\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\n\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\n\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\n\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\n\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\n\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\n\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\n\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\n\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\n\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\n\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\n\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\n\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\n\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\n\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\n\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\n\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\n\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\n\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\n\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\n\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\n\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\n\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\n\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\n\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-S1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\nBytes: 3899\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\nBytes: 2786\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\n\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887695,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":22}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782784331261}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_852683de17b343c6ac7a68","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":22,"case_id":"arb-ex06-20260630013224","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\n\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\n\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\n\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\n\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\n\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\n\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\n\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\n\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\n\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\n\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\n\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\n\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\n\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\n\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\n\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\n\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\n\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\n\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\n\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\n\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\n\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\n\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\n\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\n\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\n\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\n\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\n\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\n\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\n\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\n\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\n\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\n\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\n\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\n\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\n\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\n\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\n\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\n\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\n\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\n\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\n\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\n\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\n\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\n\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\n\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-S1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\nBytes: 3899\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\nBytes: 2786\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\n\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887695,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":22}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782784331261}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let's see. The user is council member C4 for an AAR case, and I need to use the MCP proxy tool to call AAR tools. The first step is to call the `aar_wait_for_opportunity` tool with an empty args object.\n\nSo, I need to structure the mcp call correctly. According to the instructions, each mcp call must have exactly a \"tool\" string and \"args\" string. No other parameters like action, server, etc.\n\nSo, the first step is to call mcp with tool \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and args as an empty JSON string. So the arguments would be {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}.\n\nThen, depending on the response, I need to proceed. If the response has state: waiting, then I have to call aar_wait_for_opportunity again with the after_version from the response. If state: ready, then read the prompt, turn, limits, etc., and opportunity id. Then review the case and evidence, use aar_get_case, list_evidence, etc., as needed. Finally submit the vote.\n\nBut the first call is to aar_wait_for_opportunity. Let me start with that.\n\nFirst, execute the mcp tool call for aar_wait_for_opportunity with empty args. So in the tool_call, name is \"mcp\", arguments should be {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}.\n\nI need to check the exact parameters for the mcp function. The mcp function's parameters require `tool` and `args` as JSON string. So the arguments for mcp should be a JSON object with those fields. So \"tool\" is the tool name, \"args\" is a string of the JSON for the tool's parameters.\n\nYes. So the correct structure is:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"mcp\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n    \"args\": \"{}\"\n  }\n}\n\nBecause the args for the tool itself is an empty JSON, so {\"args\": \"{}\"}.\n\nThen, once that's called, I need to process the response. But right now, I have to make the first call.\n\nLet's do that. Once the response comes back, then check the state. If it's waiting, then call again with after_version. If ready, get the details, then proceed to get the case and evidence.\n\nBut the current step is to start by calling aar_wait_for_opportunity with empty args.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_852683de17b343c6ac7a68","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":2405,"output":556,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2961,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782784327169,"responseId":"gen-1782784327-Atvhg06vqfE2ZlXmylc7","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_852683de17b343c6ac7a68","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 22\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630013224\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 887695\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":22,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630013224\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\\n\\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\\n\\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\\n\\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\\n\\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\\n\\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\\n\\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\\n\\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\\n\\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\\n\\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\\n\\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\\n\\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\\n\\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\\n\\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\\n\\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\\n\\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\\n\\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\\n\\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\\n\\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\\n\\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\\n\\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\\n\\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\\n\\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\\n\\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\\n\\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\\n\\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\\n\\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\\n\\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\\n\\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\\n\\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\\n\\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\\n\\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\\n\\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\\n\\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\\n\\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\\n\\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\\n\\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\\n\\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\\n\\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\n\\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\\n\\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\\n\\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\n\\n\\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\n\\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\\\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\\n\\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\n\\n\\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \\\"just sworn in\\\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\n\\n\\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nPublisher: The White House\\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\n\\nExtracted relevant page text:\\n\\n\\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\\nBytes: 3899\\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\\nBytes: 2786\\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887695,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":14,\"version\":22}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":22,"case_id":"arb-ex06-20260630013224","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\n\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case is straightforward, but it is source-sensitive. The proposition does not turn on whether the United States applied pressure to Venezuela, whether strikes or naval activity occurred, or whether Venezuelan proxy forces acted. It turns on a narrower question: did U.S. ground forces physically enter Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity, before the January 31, 2026 expiration, in an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government, or establish operational control of a major population center?\n\nAt this opening stage the AAR record is empty. There is no admitted case-packet evidence, no submitted source material, and no exhibit whose custody or provenance can yet be weighed. That matters. Plaintiff will not ask the council to decide from headlines, snippets, or counsel’s private investigation. The proof that should decide this case is the proof named in the proposition itself: official Department of Defense or White House confirmation, with United Nations Security Council records as the binding fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\n\nThe real dispute will likely be over characterization, not merely geography. Physical entry by U.S. personnel into Venezuela is necessary, but not alone sufficient if the record shows only an excluded category: a targeted strike, naval blockade, cyber operation, proxy action, or a special operations raid without a territorial objective. The edge case is especially important: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO under this market. Plaintiff therefore expects to carry the burden by showing not just boots on Venezuelan soil, but combat-capacity ground forces tied to an objective within the proposition: removal of the sitting government or operational control/territorial control, rather than a freestanding raid.\n\nThe evidence we will seek to place before you in the next phase should answer four questions. First, source: is there an official DoD or White House statement confirming deployment of U.S. ground forces, and if any official sources conflict, what do Security Council records say? Second, location and personnel: did U.S. personnel, not only proxy forces or remote systems, cross into Venezuelan sovereign territory? Third, capacity: were those personnel operating as combat ground forces rather than merely advisers, evacuees, or remote-support personnel? Fourth, objective: did the operation aim at one of the qualifying territorial or governmental-control objectives, and does the official record avoid the market’s express exclusions?\n\nBecause the current record contains no admitted evidence, provenance issues are for later source admissions. When evidence is offered, the council should give greatest weight to primary official records preserved with dates, retrieval provenance, and faithful text or transcript captures. Secondary reporting, if any, should be used only to locate and test those primary materials. The plaintiff’s position is that the decisive official materials will satisfy the preponderance standard for YES, but the council should require the source chain and the mission-objective link before crediting that conclusion.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense begins with the narrow terms of the proposition. This case is not about whether the United States opposed Venezuela’s government, used force in the region, supported partners, imposed pressure, conducted strikes, or generated international controversy. It resolves YES only if the plaintiff proves a much more specific event: U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and did so with a qualifying territorial or governmental-control objective.\n\nThe current AAR record matters. After inspection, there is no admitted evidence, no case-packet file, no submitted source material, and no exhibit. The plaintiff’s opening properly acknowledges that the burden is source-sensitive, but it does not itself prove any of the required facts. At this stage the council has no official Department of Defense statement, no White House confirmation, and no Security Council record admitted as evidence. The plaintiff therefore has not yet supplied the source foundation that the proposition itself requires.\n\nThe defense theory is straightforward: each element is independent, and a missing link defeats YES. First, the source must be an official DoD or White House confirmation, with UN Security Council records becoming binding only if those official U.S. sources conflict. Second, the confirmation must establish U.S. personnel physically entering Venezuelan territory, not merely aircraft, ships, cyber tools, advisers outside the country, or proxy forces acting under U.S. direction. Third, those personnel must be ground forces in a combat capacity. Fourth, the mission objective must be one of the qualifying objectives: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Fifth, it must have occurred by the expiration date.\n\nThe exclusions are not footnotes; they are central. Targeted strikes resolve NO. Naval blockades resolve NO. Cyber operations resolve NO. Special-operations raids without territorial objectives resolve NO. Proxy forces resolve NO unless U.S. personnel themselves are physically present. Even capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly carved out as NO. Those carveouts prevent the council from collapsing a dramatic military or diplomatic episode into this proposition unless the record proves the specific ground-entry and territorial-objective requirements.\n\nThe strongest possible plaintiff case will likely try to turn a reported U.S. action in Venezuela into proof of boots on the ground and a government-removal objective. The defense will test that characterization against the official source chain and the market language. A public controversy, a Security Council debate, or a broad phrase such as “action in Venezuela” would not be enough unless the admitted record connects it to U.S. ground troops, combat capacity, Venezuelan sovereign territory, and a qualifying objective.\n\nWhen evidence is later offered, the council should weigh provenance and custody carefully: dated official pages or faithful captures should matter most; secondary reporting should be useful only as a path to primary sources; and any source-access gaps, conflicting statements, or ambiguous mission descriptions should reduce weight. On this record, the disciplined starting point is NO unless and until plaintiff admits primary evidence satisfying every required element by a preponderance.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff now offers the official source proof the openings identified as decisive.\n\nThe controlling source requirement is satisfied by PX-1, an official War.gov/Department of War article. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, “the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela” against a fortified military fortress in Caracas. PX-1 further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple service branches, and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” That is official U.S. confirmation of U.S. ground personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, in combat capacity, before the Jan. 31 expiration.\n\nThe objective element is also met by a preponderance. PX-1 does not describe a mere remote strike, blockade, cyber operation, or proxy action. It describes a U.S. military operation in Caracas that captured Maduro, after which he was “out of power.” More importantly, PX-1 records the President saying the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement” could be identified and that a group of people was “running [Venezuela]” until it could be put back on track. That official language ties the ground operation to removal of the sitting ruler and temporary operational control over the governmental transition. The proposition does not require permanent occupation; it requires a qualifying objective. Removing the sitting government and controlling the transition are qualifying objectives.\n\nPX-2, the White House Rubio release, supplies both corroboration and the best adverse context. It repeatedly characterizes the event as a “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest,” and Rubio says it was not an invasion or extended military operation. Plaintiff does not hide that language. But those words do not defeat YES. The market’s required event is not “invasion” or “extended war.” It is ground forces entering Venezuelan territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective. PX-2 also confirms the broader policy objective: Venezuela was to “move in a certain direction”; the U.S. retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest” until “changes are made”; and continued U.S. pressure would remain until the U.S.-specified conditions were addressed.\n\nThe defense will lean on the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. The admitted record is materially stronger than that edge case. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power, identifies a replacement-transition process, and says the U.S. would oversee and have people running Venezuela in the interim. PX-2’s denial of “invasion” limits the form and duration of the operation, but it does not erase the ground-based force in Caracas or the official transition-control statements. This was not just a person seized and flown away with no territorial or governmental consequence; it was a U.S. operation in Venezuela’s capital that removed the ruler and asserted operational control over what came next.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources confirm U.S. armed forces conducted Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas; U.S. ground forces were present through the ground-based extraction force; the event occurred before expiration; and official statements link the operation to Maduro’s removal from power and U.S. oversight of the transition. What it does not prove: permanent occupation, prolonged invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Those are not required. The record’s provenance is strong: both exhibits are official U.S. government sources, submitted with URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring resort to UNSC fallback.\n\nOn this record, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff’s own official exhibits defeat the proposition. The defense does not need to dispute that PX-1 and PX-2 are official U.S. sources, or that PX-1 describes some U.S. personnel in Caracas. The decisive issue is the market’s limiting language: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is expressly NO, and special-operations raids without territorial objectives are also NO.\n\nStart with what PX-1 proves. It describes “the capture” of Nicolas Maduro after an overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Caracas. It quotes President Trump saying the operation was against a fortified military fortress “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes Operation Absolute Resolve as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros,” involving special operations forces, aircraft cover, and a “ground-based extraction force in Caracas.” Secretary Hegseth called it a “massive joint military and law enforcement raid.” Those words establish a capture/extraction/arrest mission, not an operation whose objective was to seize or hold territory or establish operational control of Caracas.\n\nPX-2 makes the limiting characterization even clearer. The White House release says the action was “not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation.” It calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” It discusses continuing U.S. pressure, oil quarantine, sanctions-related vessel seizures, drug-boat targeting, and policy demands. That is not territorial occupation. It is coercive policy pressure after a raid.\n\nThe proposition’s edge case was written for exactly this dispute: “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff tries to avoid that clause by pointing to PX-1’s post-capture statements that Maduro was out of power and that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until a transition. But the event element is not “a raid followed by U.S. political influence over a transition.” It is ground troops entering Venezuela with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted sources identify the operational objective as capture, extraction, arrest, and bringing Maduro to justice. They do not state that U.S. ground forces seized, held, occupied, administered, or controlled Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\n\nNor does “removing the sitting government” save plaintiff’s case on this record. PX-2 says Maduro “was not the head of state” and “was an illegitimate president.” PX-1 says Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was just sworn in following Maduro’s ouster and was willing to work with the U.S. The admitted evidence therefore shows, at most, the capture of a person the U.S. described as illegitimate, followed by pressure on a successor or transition. That is precisely why the edge case separates capture from territorial occupation and resolves the former NO.\n\nWhat the evidence proves: official U.S. sources describe a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas involving a ground-based extraction force and Maduro’s capture. What it does not prove: territorial occupation; seizure or holding of territory; operational control of a major population center; or that the ground-entry objective was anything beyond capture/extraction/arrest. Provenance and custody give these official exhibits weight, but that weight favors applying the exclusions, because the adverse limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no DoD/White House conflict requiring a UN fallback.\n\nBy a preponderance, plaintiff has shown an excluded raid and capture, not the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation required for YES. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense correctly identifies the hardest issue, but it reads the exclusion too broadly and the official record too narrowly.\n\nThe edge case says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s case is not that every capture of Maduro is automatically YES. The point is that this record does not stop at capture. PX-1 says the U.S. armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; that the mission used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas; that Maduro was then “out of power”; and that the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition, with a group of people “running [Venezuela]” in the interim. Those are not stray political comments unrelated to the event. They are the official explanation of what Operation Absolute Resolve accomplished and what control followed it.\n\nThe defense tries to make “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” mutually exclusive with a qualifying objective. They are not. A raid can be the method. Capture can be the immediate tactical action. Arrest can be the law-enforcement disposition. The proposition asks for the objective of the military operation. PX-1’s stated results and transition-control language show that the operation’s objective was not merely to seize a body and leave Venezuela unchanged; it was to remove Maduro from power and place the transition under U.S. oversight.\n\nNor does plaintiff need to prove permanent occupation of territory. The event definition is disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Defense focuses on the first and third forms while minimizing the second. If U.S. ground forces enter Caracas in combat capacity, remove the ruler, and official sources say the U.S. will oversee the country’s transition, that satisfies at least the “removing the sitting government” prong. The temporary-running language also supports operational control, but the removal prong alone is enough.\n\nPX-2’s adverse wording does not change that. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit the scale and duration. They do not deny physical ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, or removal from power. PX-2 also says the U.S. retained options after the raid until “changes are made” and wanted Venezuela to move in a U.S.-specified direction. That corroborates, rather than negates, the transition-control objective.\n\nFinally, defense’s reliance on Rubio’s statement that Maduro was not the legitimate head of state should not control the market’s “sitting government” language. The record shows he was the Venezuelan leader captured in Caracas and then out of power; the U.S. cannot avoid the removal prong by labeling the target illegitimate after removing him.\n\nThe official sources have strong provenance and no source conflict. Taken together, they prove more than an excluded bare capture: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that removed Venezuela’s ruler and put the transition under U.S. oversight. That is YES by a preponderance.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal turns on a category shift: it treats downstream political consequences as if they prove the objective of the ground-entry operation. The record does not support that move.\n\nPlaintiff says raid, capture, and arrest can be the method while removal and transition control were the objective. But PX-1 itself supplies the stated operational purpose: the operation was against a fortified location “to bring” Maduro “to justice”; Maduro and his wife would face criminal proceedings; and the mission was a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” PX-2 then calls the event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” while also saying it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. The admitted official sources therefore identify the objective and character of the ground action as capture/extraction/arrest, not territorial occupation or population-center control.\n\nThe market language anticipated exactly this ambiguity. It does not merely exclude “minor captures”; it says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. Plaintiff’s reading would erase that edge case whenever the captured person’s removal has political consequences. Every capture of a ruler can be described as affecting power or transition. The clause only has work to do if the council distinguishes the capture itself from a territorial operation.\n\nNor has plaintiff proven the separate “operational control of a major population center” prong. Caracas is the location of the raid, not a city the record says U.S. forces controlled. Aircraft cover for an extraction force is not operational control of Caracas. A group of people later “running Venezuela” and U.S. pressure until “changes are made” are not evidence that ground troops held the capital or administered it.\n\nThe “removing the sitting government” prong also cannot be read without the edge case. PX-2 says Maduro was not head of state; PX-1 says a vice president was sworn in and was willing to work with the United States. At most, the record shows U.S. capture of a disputed or illegitimate leader followed by influence over a successor process. Without territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective, that is the proposition’s express NO scenario, not a YES.\n\nSo even accepting plaintiff’s strongest facts, the decisive missing link remains: an official source saying the ground operation’s objective was more than capture, extraction, arrest, and pressure. The record has no such statement. It has the opposite. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you official-source proof on every required element.\n\nFirst, source and timing. PX-1 is an official Department of War/War.gov source. It reports President Trump’s Jan. 3, 2026 announcement of Operation Absolute Resolve, describing an overnight operation that occurred before the Jan. 31 expiration. PX-2 is an official White House source. No DoD/White House conflict requires resort to the UN fallback.\n\nSecond, physical entry and combat capacity. PX-1 does not describe only aircraft, ships, cyber tools, proxy forces, or outside advisers. It says the United States armed forces conducted a military operation in Venezuela’s capital; the operation involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces from multiple branches; and more than 150 aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas. A ground-based extraction force in Caracas is U.S. personnel physically inside Venezuelan sovereign territory. The fortified target, aircraft cover, special operations forces, and military-operation framing establish combat capacity by a preponderance.\n\nThird, objective. This is the only serious dispute. The defense says the words “raid,” “capture,” and “arrest” end the case. They do not. Those words describe method and immediate tactical act; they do not erase the operation’s official consequences and stated transition control. PX-1 says Maduro was out of power. PX-1 says the U.S. would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 says a group of people was running Venezuela in the interim. PX-1 says the successor was willing to work with the United States to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-2 adds that U.S. policy was to move Venezuela in a certain direction and that U.S. options and pressure would continue until changes were made.\n\nThat record satisfies the proposition in two independent ways. The operation removed the sitting ruler from power. And the official transition language shows operational control over what came next, at least temporarily. The proposition does not require permanent occupation, a declared invasion, or seizure of all Venezuelan territory. Its prongs are disjunctive: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The admitted official sources prove the removal prong and strongly support operational control.\n\nThe defense’s edge-case argument matters, but it is not this case. The edge case excludes capture of a head of state without territorial occupation. If the record only showed Maduro grabbed, flown away, and no governmental-control consequence, plaintiff would lose. But the official record says more: the U.S. ground operation in Caracas removed Maduro from power and was followed by U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela’s transition. Defense cannot sever the capture from the official description of what it accomplished.\n\nPX-2’s adverse language also has its place. “Not an invasion” and “not an extended military operation” limit scale and duration. They do not deny ground entry, combat capacity, Caracas location, removal from power, or U.S. transition control. A short operation can still have a qualifying objective.\n\nWhat the record does not prove is permanent occupation or broad territorial seizure. Those are unnecessary. What it does prove, through official U.S. sources with clean provenance, is U.S. combat ground entry into Caracas for Operation Absolute Resolve, before expiration, with the objective and effect of removing Venezuela’s ruler and controlling the transition. On a preponderance standard, the proposition resolves YES.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the final question is not whether Operation Absolute Resolve was serious, controversial, or involved U.S. personnel in Caracas. The defense’s closing accepts, for purposes of decision, the strongest record facts plaintiff has: PX-1 is an official War.gov source; PX-2 is an official White House source; the event was before January 31, 2026; and PX-1 describes a ground-based extraction force in Caracas covered by U.S. military assets.\n\nEven with those assumptions, plaintiff still must prove the qualifying objective. That is where the record fails.\n\nThe official source language is not ambiguous about the mission’s immediate purpose. PX-1 says the operation was conducted “to bring” Maduro “to justice.” It says Maduro and his wife would face criminal court proceedings tied to a U.S. indictment. It describes the mission as a joint military and law-enforcement mission “to capture the Maduros.” It refers to extraction. Secretary Hegseth called it a joint military and law-enforcement raid. PX-2 then calls the same event “this raid and this capture and this arrest,” and says it was not an invasion and not an extended military operation.\n\nThose are not defense glosses; they are the admitted official sources. They prove a capture/extraction/arrest operation. They do not prove an operation whose objective was to seize or hold Venezuelan territory, occupy Caracas, administer a major population center, or place U.S. ground forces in operational control of the city.\n\nPlaintiff’s answer is to rely on aftermath: Maduro was out of power, the U.S. would oversee a transition, people were “running” Venezuela, and U.S. pressure would continue until changes were made. But the proposition asks for the objective of the ground-troop operation. Political leverage after a raid is not the same as territorial occupation or operational control by ground forces. The record never says U.S. troops held Caracas. It never says they administered the capital. It never says they stayed to control a population center. It says aircraft covered an extraction force during a raid.\n\nThe edge case resolves the case. “Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO.” Plaintiff’s reading drains that clause of meaning. If every capture that removes a ruler from power automatically satisfies the “removing the sitting government” prong, then the express capture edge case can almost never apply. The better reading is the one the defense has advanced: a capture or arrest remains NO unless the record proves something more in the operation itself, such as territorial occupation or a qualifying territorial-control objective.\n\nPlaintiff has not proved that something more. PX-2 even narrows it: not an invasion, not extended military action, a raid/capture/arrest, followed by pressure and options. That is precisely the kind of excluded event the proposition separates from a true ground operation to seize, hold, remove by territorial control, or control a major population center.\n\nThe evidence has strong provenance, but its weight cuts against YES because the limiting language is in the official sources themselves. There is no source conflict and no UN fallback issue. On this record, plaintiff has proven an excluded capture raid, not the qualifying operation required by the proposition. The council should resolve the event NO.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-S1\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nPublisher: U.S. Department of War / Pentagon News\nDate: Jan. 3, 2026\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolás Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\n\nPresident Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. … It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolás Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\nThe president added that both Maduro and his also-captured wife, Cilia Flores de Maduro, will now face criminal court proceedings tied to a 2020 indictment from the U.S. Department of Justice on multiple federal charges, including narco-terrorism and drug trafficking.\n\nEarlier in the day, Trump posted a photo to social media showing a blindfolded and handcuffed Nicolás Maduro in custody aboard the U.S. Navy amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima.\n\nLabeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces — including special operations forces — from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\n\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. … We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. … This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\nHe added that the mission to extract the Maduros — in which there were no U.S. casualties — was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\n\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer,\" Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, who was also in attendance at Mar-a-Lago, told the media.\n\nWith Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\n\n\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] … give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\nThe president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was \"just sworn in\" [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\n\n\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere — and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nPublisher: The White House\nDate shown in related/release context: January 2026\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\n\nExtracted relevant page text:\n\n\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn’t require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation… We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they’ll get congressional notification.\"\n\n\"The whole foreign policy apparatus thinks everything is Libya, everything is Iraq, everything is Afghanistan. This is not the Middle East, and our mission here is very different. This is the Western Hemisphere.\"\n\n\"The most immediate changes are the ones that are in the national interests of the United States. That’s why we’re involved here — because of how it applies and has a direct impact on the United States.\"\n\n\"What we are going to react to is very simple: what do you do? Not what you’re saying publicly, what happens… Do the drugs stop coming? Are the changes made? Is Iran expelled? Is Hezbollah and Iran no longer able to operate against our interests from Venezuela?\"\n\n\"It’s running policy — the policy with regards to this. We want Venezuela to move in a certain direction because not only do we think it’s good for the people of Venezuela, it’s in our national interest.\"\n\n\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest… until such time as changes are made.\"\n\n\"In the Biden Administration, they had a $25 million reward for [Maduro’s] capture — so we have a reward for his capture but we’re not going to enforce it? That’s the difference between President Trump and everybody else… President Trump did something about it.\"\n\n\"Until they address [the problems], they will continue to face this oil quarantine. They will continue to face pressure from the United States. We will continue to target drug boats if they try to run towards the United States. We will continue to seize the boats that are sanctioned with court orders. We will continue to do that and potentially other things until the things we need to see addressed are addressed… The number one thing we care about is the safety, security, wellbeing, and prosperity of the United States.\"\n\n\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as ‘President Maduro’ and the ‘head of state.’ He was not the head of state.\"\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_d7a52fba7358_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d7a52fba7358)\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nSHA-256: `d7a52fba7358ed83288449971ed45e53e9fb0e327d3566b1ff781bed681bb241`\nBytes: 3899\nRelevance: Primary official U.S. source confirming Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela, U.S. armed forces/military operation, ground-based extraction force, capture/removal of Maduro, and U.S. transition-control statements.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] White House Rubio release on Operation Absolute Resolve and Venezuela policy (ev_37f9459e255e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-37f9459e255e)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nSHA-256: `37f9459e255e743b42ea8aed527b8edeb8eebb15594da6fc1abf928f4431ae89`\nBytes: 2786\nRelevance: Official White House source bearing on operation characterization, objectives, continued U.S. pressure/control policy, and adverse statements calling the action a raid rather than an invasion or extended operation.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-search and weight ledger\nRecord inspection found no preexisting evidence. Plaintiff searched official War.gov/DoD/SOUTHCOM and White House sources, plus secondary and adverse leads. The two submitted exhibits were selected because official U.S. sources control under the proposition. Secondary reporting and social posts were not submitted because the official sources were available and more probative. Material adverse language in the White House release was preserved: the administration called the event a raid/capture/arrest and denied an invasion or extended operation. The remaining unresolved source gap is the full press-conference video/transcript, which may matter only if later argument challenges the context of the official article excerpts.\n\n[defendant] Defense element analysis of official exhibits\nDefense inspected the live record, listed evidence, statted both plaintiff submissions, and read the full bytes of both text exhibits. PX-1/DX-1 proves official source language for a military/law-enforcement capture/extraction/raid in Caracas and a ground-based extraction force, but does not state territorial occupation, seizure/holding of territory, or operational control of Caracas. PX-2/DX-2 supplies adverse official characterization: not an invasion, not an extended military operation, and a raid/capture/arrest followed by pressure and policy demands. No new evidence was submitted because the existing official exhibits are sufficient to argue the market exclusion.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, defense rechecked the record and evidence list. Plaintiff rebuttal added no new evidence or changed metadata. The only record sources remain the two official text exhibits already read in full during arguments; no external source was needed because plaintiff's rebuttal raised a characterization issue, not a new factual source issue.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T02:06:58.95052376Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887695,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":14,"version":22}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782784331261}]}
