" rather than an invasion or extended operation, which supports the edge case exception.\\n\\nThe exhibits suggest this operation was primarily a capture operation with immediate consequences (Maduro was out of power, new leadership was in place that was willing to work with the U.S.), but there are no specific statements about U.S. ground forces taking control of territory, holding specific territory, or establishing operational control over Caracas or any Venezuelan territory.\\n\\nLet me check the specific arguments from both sides:\\n\\nPlaintiff's main argument is that:\\n- The U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity\\n- They removed Maduro from power\\n- They asserted operational control over what came next (U.S. oversight of transition, people \"running Venezuela\" temporarily)\\n- The proposition allows for \"removing the sitting government\" or \"establishing operational control of a major population center\" as sufficient conditions\\n- The capture of Maduro was not just an isolated action but part of a broader operation that resulted in U.S. oversight and control over Venezuela's transition\\n\\nDefendant's main argument is that:\\n- The operation was explicitly characterized as a \"raid,\" \"capture,\" and \"arrest\" by both official sources\\n- This is precisely what the edge case addresses: \"Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\"\\n- Maduro was described as \"not the head of state\" but rather \"an illegitimate president\" or a \"deposed strongman\"\\n- The \"U.S. oversight of transition\" was more akin to ongoing political pressure and policy influence rather than operational control by U.S. ground forces in the territory\\n- The operation did not involve \"seizing or holding territory\" or \"establishing operational control of a major population center\" but rather was limited to a capture operation\\n\\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, I need to determine if the proposition is satisfied.\\n\\nKey question: does the operation satisfy \"removing the sitting government\" or \"establishing operational control of a major population center\"?\\n\\nFor \"removing the sitting government\":\\n- Maduro was referred to as \"outlaw dictator\" and \"deposed strongman\" in PX-1 and as \"illegitimate president\" in PX-2\\n- The U.S. stated \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state.\"\\n- If he was not the legitimate head of state, then \"removing the sitting government\" may not apply, as there was no legitimate government to remove in the first place\\n- The operation was to \"bring Maduro to justice\" on narcotics charges, not specifically to remove a legitimate government\\n\\nFor \"establishing operational control of a major population center\":\\n- PX-1 says \"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified\"\\n- \"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track\"\\n- However, this oversight appears to be more about political influence and policy guidance rather than U.S. ground forces exercising direct operational control of Caracas or Venezuela's territory\\n- The White House release says \"This was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation\" and calls it \"this raid and this capture and this arrest\"\\n- There's no mention of U.S. forces occupying territory, establishing checkpoints, administering governance, or exercising direct control over Caracas\\n\\nThe edge case explicitly states: \"Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\"\\n\\nSince the U.S. explicitly referred to Maduro as not a legitimate head of state and characterized the operation as a raid/capture/arrest that was not an invasion or extended military operation, this appears to fall squarely under the edge case scenario. The operation di